<p><strong>Sleepers by Lorenzo Carcaterra: A Poignant Exploration of Innocence Lost</strong></p>
<p><strong>Question 1: What is the premise of Lorenzo Carcaterra's "Sleepers"?</strong></p>
<p>Answer: "Sleepers" is a non-fiction account that follows the lives of four boys who were falsely accused and imprisoned for a crime they did not commit. Carcaterra, a journalist, spent years interviewing the real-life subjects of the book and delved into the systemic failures and injustices that led to their wrongful conviction.</p>
<p><strong>Question 2: Who are the four main characters in the story?</strong></p>
<p>Answer: The four boys at the heart of "Sleepers" are Michael Sullivan, Lorenzo "Shakes" Carcaterra (the author himself), John Reilly, and Tommy Marcano. Each of them comes from a troubled background and seeks solace and a sense of belonging in their friendship.</p>
<p><strong>Question 3: What is the significance of the Wilkinson Home for Boys?</strong></p>
<p>Answer: Wilkinson Home is a juvenile detention center where the boys are sent after being convicted of their crime. It is a harsh and abusive environment where the boys are subjected to physical and sexual violence. Their experiences at Wilkinson serve as a catalyst for their transformation from innocent children into hardened survivors.</p>
<p><strong>Question 4: How does the theme of innocence lost play out in the book?</strong></p>
<p>Answer: "Sleepers" explores the profound loss of innocence that the boys experience as they are stripped of their freedom and subjected to the horrors of Wilkinson Home. Their experiences shatter their childhood dreams and leave them grappling with the lasting effects of trauma and abuse.</p>
<p><strong>Question 5: What impact did the book have on the real-life subjects?</strong></p>
<p>Answer: The publication of "Sleepers" brought national attention to the case and helped to exonerate the wrongfully accused boys. It also led to reforms in the juvenile justice system and raised awareness about the dangers of false convictions. The book remains a powerful testimony to the resilience of the human spirit and the importance of fighting for justice.</p>